ce:section.ce:para:
Despite these significant technical advancements in other domains, the application of PPINN—which learns a generalized solution manifold across multiple parameter configurations rather than solving a single fixed equation—to the highly dynamic and multi-parameter domain of battery SOC estimation has not yet been studied. This paper fills this research gap by proposing a novel PPINN framework designed for robust battery SOC estimation, directly overcoming the parameter dependency inherent in conventional methods and ensuring adaptability across diverse operating scenarios. The proposed method adopts a hypernetwork-based latent space approach that uniquely satisfies three critical requirements for battery SOC estimation: (1) instantaneous weight generation, enabling the model to interpret initial battery states as dynamic conditions and learn a generalized solution space across a wide range of operating scenarios; (2) non-linear expressivity through SVD-based weight modulation, overcoming the spectral bias of input concatenation and the linear limitations of operator learning [31]; and (3) structural integration of physics-based parameters and data-driven temporal predictions within a unified architecture, ensuring that estimations are grounded in evolving data trends while remaining consistent with underlying electrochemical principles [32]. The result is a physics-informed learning framework that enables a single model to accurately estimate SOC across diverse conditions without relying on precise model parameters. The main contributions of this paper are:

                           1)

The first study, to the best of our knowledge, to adopt PPINN for EV battery SOC estimation and to further develop it through integration with temporal prediction;


                           2)

Battery parameter estimation independence, eliminating model-based precision requirements via a hypernetwork with dynamic weight generation and adaptive learning capabilities;


                           3)

Robust physics-informed learning, which enables a single model to accurately capture battery SOC characteristics across diverse operating conditions;


                           4)

Comprehensive experimental validation demonstrating notable robustness to missing data across various temperature conditions and driving cycles.

The data-driven training loss curves for each method are presented in Fig. 10 (a). The proposed PPINN consistently achieves stable convergence with lower final loss values compared to the comparative methods. The loss trajectories for the LSTM and [18] are identical because the EKF component in [18] operates only during inference and does not participate in gradient-based training. In contrast, [17] exhibits a distinct convergence profile due to its parallel architecture where estimation errors from both the LSTM and EKF are jointly propagated during training. Fig. 10 (b) presents the LSTM loss (
L LSTM
) and physics loss (
L physics
) of the proposed PPINN separately. Both losses decrease substantially throughout the training process, converging to small values. While minor fluctuations are observed, these oscillations are a direct manifestation of the SALB mechanism actively adjusting the relative weights between the physics-based and data-driven loss components, and remain bounded within a narrow range on the logarithmic scale. Notably, occasional local increases in one loss component are not accompanied by a proportional increase in the other, confirming that the two losses do not exhibit destructive gradient conflict but instead converge together to a stable equilibrium.

Fig. 16 presents the training loss curves under the random sampling-based training data reduction condition. In Fig. 16 (a), the PPINN maintains stable convergence behavior comparable to the full dataset scenario. Fig. 16 (b) confirms that the LSTM loss (
L LSTM
) and physics loss (
L physics
) similarly converge without destructive gradient conflict, demonstrating that the SALB mechanism and physics-informed constraints effectively regularize the learning process under missing data conditions.
